					<div class="content-intro-text">
						<h1>Management Information Systems</h1>
													<p class="author"><strong>Author:</strong>
								Paul Geeders</p>
																								
													<p class="date"><strong>Date:</strong>
							30/12/2004</p>
																									<p class="intro">Introduction:</p>
							 <p>







 




  
  

	
	<a href="/var/knowledge/storage/images/media/images/photos_people/scientist_computer/224999-1-eng-GB/scientist_computer.jpg" rel="lightbox[]">	
	  </a>
	
	
	
	
  	






	 
  





	In most countries, the environmental information necessary to solve the complex problems of society, economy and environment, is scattered over different Ministries, organisations and institutions. This is the result of many decades of specialisation, isolation, suspicion and competition. However, <b>integrated problems demand integrated solutions</b>, and these solutions can only be developed on the basis of <b>integrated information</b>. In response to this need, the concept of Clearing Houses was developed.</p>
						
						
						
						<br/>&nbsp;
					</div> 
					<br class="cl">
				</div> 
				 
			
				<div id="content-item">
											<div class="box-content">
							<a class="storylist" href="/en/layout/set/print/content/view/full/1002">Print</a>
																				</div> 
						<br class="cl">
		
					 
	
				</div> 
			
				<div id="main-content" class="content view">					

	                          
			

	<!-- BEGIN BODY TEXT -->	
	
			<div class="stdtext">	
			
 <p><b>Clearing Houses</b> form a 'portal' on the Internet where different providers advertise their information products and related services, and where users can find the information they need. The development of Clearing Houses for specialised information helps to improve the availability and accessibility of information thus improving the quality of the policy processes they are intended to serve. Hundreds of Clearing Houses have been established on the Internet, for various disciplines and at different scales (state, country, regional, global) and many of them relate to environmental information.</p> <p>Most Clearing Houses have been established in the context of projects, usually with temporary funding. However, only few survive after the project funding has ended; these are the ones that succeed to balance their costs with the income from the services and products they provide. The main bottlenecks that need to be addressed to ensure the survival of Clearing Houses are:</p> 
<ul>
 
<li> the <b>continuity of the funding</b> - who is willing to pay for the added value that Clearing Houses offer? The user? The government? International organisations?  </li>
 
<li>  <b>institutional competition</b> <b>problems</b> - many providers are not willing to make their environmental information available through a Clearing House, as they are afraid that someone else will 'make money out of their information'.  </li>
 
<li>  <b>availability of s</b> <b>pecialised environmental data/information managers</b> - setting up and managing a Clearing House requires ICT expertise as well as expertise in the specific field of the Clearing House; these experts are not readily available, often only on-the-job training can produce the required expertise.  </li>
 
<li>  <b>standardisation of data/information</b> - the almost complete lack of international standards for environmental data and information archival hamper the process of searching for and linking with relevant information; also most data and information archives are not provided with <b>metadata</b>, a prerequisite for successful search and identification actions. </li>
 
</ul>
 <p>Consequently, most Clearing Houses act as 'portals', a grouped, systematic compilation of links to a variety of related websites, as can be seen from the various links included with this dossier. They are not able to perform an effective integration of the information from different databases. Selecting from the multitude of environmental information obtained through the different links, the user has to manually perform this integration in order to obtain useful information in response to a question.</p> <p>The Internet acts as a encyclopaedia; however, it does not always provide 'an intelligent answer to an intelligent question'. On the contrary, the increasing volume of information on the Internet makes it even more cumbersome to obtain the 'intelligent answer' required. In many countries and academic centres, efforts are underway to solve this problem and develop 'intelligent' information portals, which use innovative software to provide a weighed response to the user, based on searches performed in various databases.</p> <p><b>Examples of successful environmental information systems</b> </p> <p>1. <i>ECMWF, European Centre for MediumRange Weather Forecast, Reading, UK.</i> </p> <p>The principal objectives of the ECMWF centre are [*]:</p> 
<ul>
 
<li> the development of numerical methods for medium-range weather forecasting;  </li>
 
<li> the preparation, on a regular basis, of medium-range weather forecasts for distribution to the meteorological services of the Member States;  </li>
 
<li> scientific and technical research directed to the improvement of these forecasts;  </li>
 
<li> collection and storage of appropriate meteorological data. </li>
 
</ul>
 <p>In addition, the Centre:</p> 
<ul>
 
<li> makes available a proportion of its computing facilities to its Member States for their research;  </li>
 
<li> assists in implementing the programmes of the World Meteorological Organisation;  </li>
 
<li> provides advanced training to the scientific staff of the Member States in the field of numerical weather prediction;  </li>
 
<li> makes the data in its extensive archives available to outside bodies. </li>
 
</ul>
 <p>The ECMWF acts on the basis of a Convention between the Member States. This Convention states: 'The organs of the Centre shall be the Council and the Director. The Council shall be assisted by a Scientific Advisory Committee and a Finance Committee.' The Council has since established further Committees: Technical Advisory Committee, Advisory Committee on Data Policy, Advisory Committee of Co-operating States. The Council and Committees meet at regular periods through the year.</p> <p>Information on weather and climate have great relevance for agriculture and rural development, and as such, reliable medium range weather forecasts are of great economic importance for the ACP countries. Therefore in due time the establishment of similar centres in the ACP regions should be considered.</p> <p>2. <i>ODIN-IOC, Ocean Data and Information Network of IOC</i> </p> <p>Access to, and effective utilization of data and information for management and exploitation of the marine environment and resources is one of the major challenges facing Intergovernmental Oceanographic Commission (IOC) member states. The success of development strategies will depend to a great extent on the availability and use of scientific and technical information in a form that can be readily understood and applied. The member states need to establish mechanisms for collection, quality control, analysis, interpretation and dissemination of data and information. Though several programmes initiated at the national, regional and global level have generated substantial amounts of data and information, these have not been effectively used for national development. This has mainly been due to limited access to data collected in the framework of these programmes, and the lack of skills for analysis and interpretation of the data.</p> <p>As a first step to improve this situation for the IOC Member States in Africa, the Ocean Data and Information Network for Africa (ODINAFRICA) [*] was established in 1999. It is currently formed by twenty Member States of the Intergovernmental Oceanographic Commission of UNESCO. These include Benin, Cameroon, Comoros, Cote D'Ivoire, Gabon, Ghana, Guinea, Kenya, Madagascar, Mauritania, Mauritius, Morocco, Mozambique, Nigeria, Senegal, Seychelles, South Africa, United Republic of Tanzania, Togo and Tunisia. The aims of ODINAFRICA are to:</p> 
<ul>
 
<li> enable member states from Africa to get access to data available in other data centres,  </li>
 
<li> develop skills for manipulation of data and preparation of data and information products, and  </li>
 
<li> develop infrastructure for archival, analysis and dissemination of the data and information products. </li>
 
</ul>
 <p>The development of the network has received support from UNESCO-IOC and the Government of Flanders, Belgium.</p> <p>Note that ODINAFRICA resulted from initiatives in the region since 1987; this forms a clear indication of the long time needed to successfully establish this type of regional co-operation. A major element of the process has always been to carefully assess the <b>requirements in the various Member States</b> through missions, interviews and meetings, in order to ensure that the results of the project would meet these requirements. Implementation of the project included close and continuous feedback with counterparts in all participating countries. The project is intended to improve exchange, which implies that the participants not only access the contents of the system, but also contribute their own data, information and experience.</p> <p>On the basis of the success of ODINAFRICA, a similar project ODINCARSA with similar objectives was initiated in 2001 for the IOC Member States of the Caribbean and South America [*].</p> <p>The lessons learned from these successful IOC regional projects are of relevance to ACP countries. Moreover, the coastal and marine environmental information circulating within these networks can be of immediate value for agricultural and rural development.</p> <p>3. <i>European Community Biodiversity Clearing-House Mechanism</i> </p> <p>This web-based portal was developed since 1999 and its actual implementation took place in 2001. It contains a wide range of European and global links relevant for biodiversity and environmental management. It links to the Convention on Biodiversity, the relevant organs of the EU organisation in Brussels, the European Environment Agency EEA, the Global Biodiversity Information Facility GBIF and many others. Information is presented on biodiversity conventions, projects and programmes, and on opportunities for funding for biodiversity related projects. The site contains a well-updated news section and a section on meetings and events. A specific element of the site is devoted to technical biodiversity issues: data profiles, monitoring and indicators, directories and reference services, red lists, alien species and selected species groups.</p> <p>This portal could form a valuable reference for biodiversity related activities in the ACP countries, and could be used to promote the biodiversity sites of the ACP countries. It might be considered to establish similar biodiversity portals for the three ACP regions.</p> <p><b>Conclusions</b> </p> <p>Management Information Systems <b>form an essential tool</b> for agricultural and rural development and National Resource Management (NRM) in the ACP countries, providing environmental (and other) data and information for daily operations, as well as for planning and decision-making.</p> <p>In several ACP countries, a number of integrated environmental information systems have been established or are in the process of being established. These efforts and especially the <b>experience gained</b> from them would form an excellent basis for further developments of MIS in the ACP countries and regions. An exchange of these experiences should therefore be promoted, together with coordination and cooperation between the different projects.</p> <p>For agricultural and rural development in the ACP countries, much valuable environmental information and data are already available on the Internet and from other sources. However, many users are not aware and cannot access the information. The references included in this dossier are a first attempt to <b>increase awareness</b> in the ACP countries of these resources to facilitate access in ACP countries.</p> <p><b>Investments</b> need to be made by the ACP countries to obtain and or improve access to the environmental information they need. This involves investing in developing the infrastructure; a combination of appropriate technical equipment and adequately trained human resources, at the institutional, national and regional levels. This process can be realised in a <b>step-by-step approach</b>, thus spreading the financial burden.</p> <p>For countries and institutions with none or limited access to the Internet, but with access to PC's, periodic <b>publication and distribution of CD-ROM's </b>containing a number of relevant websites, which can be accessed with any browseris an option that can be pursued. There is a possible role for national, regional and international partnerships in implementing this option. </p> <p>At national and regional levels, the establishment of <b>management information systems for environmental data and information, </b>includinga <b>standard digital</b><b> framework for data collection</b>, should be considered. In these systems, the centres with a stronger information infrastructure should be encouraged to support the weaker ones in a cooperation agreement that stretches across Agency, Ministry and national boundaries. Lessons can be learned from similar systems established in several scientific disciplines (such as meteorology and marine research) in various parts in the world (ECMWF, ODINAFRICA, ODINCARSA), and on-going developments in some of the ACP countries.</p> <p><b>Financial and technical support</b> for projects aimed at developing MIS for environmental information could be found from various sources: EU-INCO/DEV, regional banks such as ADB, AFDB and IADB, UNEP-GEF, and UNDP.</p>
		</div>
		
	<!-- END BODY TEXT -->
		
			
		
	
	
			
				

		<strong class="date_small">30/12/2004</strong>
